  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/cond-mat/0202426v4</id>
    <updated>2002-11-03T22:25:02Z</updated>
    <published>2002-02-25T01:41:30Z</published>
    <title>Transport, Noise, and Conservation in the Electron Gas: How to Build a
  Credible Mesoscopic Theory</title>
    <summary>  The Boltzmann-Landau-Silin and Landauer-Buettiker-Imry theories of electron
transport are shown to be mutually incompatible. The first respects microscopic
gauge invariance, electron-hole symmetry, and the conserving sum rules for the
correlated electron gas. The second approach does not. That is directly evident
in its unphysical compressibility.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>Frederick Green</name>
    </author>
    <author>
      <name>Mukunda P. Das</name>
    </author>
