    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/cond-mat/0209275v1</id>
    <updated>2002-09-12T00:04:57Z</updated>
    <published>2002-09-12T00:04:57Z</published>
    <title>Electron dephasing near zero temperature: an experimental review</title>
    <summary>  The behavior of the electron dephasing time near zero temperature,
$\tau_\phi^0$, has recently attracted vigorous attention. This renewed interest
is primarily concerned with whether $\tau_\phi^0$ should reach a finite or an
infinite value as $T \to$ 0. While it is accepted that $\tau_\phi^0$ should
diverge if there exists only electron-electron (electron-phonon) scattering,
several recent measurements have found that $\tau_\phi^0$ depends only very
weakly on temperature, if at all, when $T$ is sufficiently low. This article
discusses the current experimental status of "the saturation problem", and
concludes that the origin(s) for this widely observed saturation are still
unresolved.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>J. J. Lin</name>
    </author>
    <author>
      <name>T. J. Li</name>
    </author>
    <author>
      <name>Y. L. Zhong</name>
    </author>
    <arxiv:doi xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">10.1143/JPSJS.72SA.7</arxiv:doi>
    <link title="doi" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1143/JPSJS.72SA.7" rel="related"/>
