  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/cond-mat/0212460v1</id>
    <updated>2002-12-18T21:33:36Z</updated>
    <published>2002-12-18T21:33:36Z</published>
    <title>Glass Transition in a Two-Dimensional Electron System in Silicon</title>
    <summary>  Large fluctuations of conductivity with time are observed in a low-mobility
two-dimensional electron system in silicon at low electron densities $n_s$ and
temperatures. A dramatic increase of the noise power ($\propto 1/f^{\alpha}$)
as $n_s$ is reduced below a certain density $n_g$, and a sharp jump of $\alpha$
at $n_s\approx n_g$, are attributed to the freezing of the electron glass at
$n_s = n_g$. The data strongly suggest that glassy dynamics persists in the
metallic phase.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>Snezana Bogdanovich</name>
    </author>
    <author>
      <name>Dragana Popovic</name>
    </author>
    <arxiv:doi xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">10.1016/S1386-9477(01)00391-5</arxiv:doi>
