  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/cond-mat/0401012v1</id>
    <updated>2004-01-02T15:17:05Z</updated>
    <published>2004-01-02T15:17:05Z</published>
    <title>Electron channels in biomolecular nanowires</title>
    <summary>  We report a first-principle study of the electronic and conduction properties
of a quadruple-helix guanine wire (G4-wire), a DNA-derivative, with inner
potassium ions. The analysis of the electronic structure highlights the
presence of energy manifolds that are equivalent to the bands of
(semi)conducting materials, and reveals the formation of extended electron
channels available for charge transport along the wire. The specific
metal-nucleobase interactions affect the electronic properties at the Fermi
level, leading the wire to behave as an intrinsically p-doped system.
</summary>
