  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/cond-mat/0606756v2</id>
    <updated>2006-07-24T20:03:06Z</updated>
    <published>2006-06-29T08:59:01Z</published>
    <title>Vibronic effects on resonant electron conduction through single molecule
  junctions</title>
    <summary>  The influence of vibrational motion on electron conduction through single
molecules bound to metal electrodes is investigated employing first-principles
electronic-structure calculations and projection-operator Green's function
methods. Considering molecular junctions where a central phenyl ring is coupled
via (alkane)thiol-bridges to gold electrodes, it is shown that -- depending on
the distance between the electronic $\pi$-system and the metal --
electronic-vibrational coupling may result in pronounced vibrational
substructures in the transmittance, a significantly reduced current as well as
a quenching of negative differential resistance effects.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>C. Benesch</name>
    </author>
    <author>
      <name>M. Thoss</name>
    </author>
