  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/1209.1020v1</id>
    <updated>2012-09-04T18:17:32Z</updated>
    <published>2012-09-04T18:17:32Z</published>
    <title>An error accounting algorithm for electron counting experiments</title>
    <summary>  Electron counting experiments attempt to provide a current of a known number
of electrons per unit time. We propose architectures utilizing a few readily
available electron-pumps or turnstiles with modest error rates of 1 part per
$10^4$ with common sensitive electrometers to achieve the desirable accuracy of
1 part in $10^8$. This is achieved not by counting all transferred electrons
but by counting only the errors of individual devices; these are less frequent
and therefore readily recognized and accounted for. Our proposal thereby eases
the route towards quantum based standards for current and capacitance.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>Michael Wulf</name>
    </author>
    <arxiv:doi xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">10.1103/PhysRevB.87.035312</arxiv:doi>
