  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/1408.2658v2</id>
    <updated>2015-05-18T12:10:45Z</updated>
    <published>2014-08-12T08:50:12Z</published>
    <title>A microwave chip-based beam splitter for low-energy guided electrons</title>
    <summary>  We demonstrate the splitting of a low-energy electron beam by means of a
microwave pseudopotential formed above a planar chip substrate. Beam splitting
arises from smoothly transforming the transverse guiding potential for an
electron beam from a single-well harmonic confinement into a double-well,
thereby generating two separated output beams with $5\,$mm lateral spacing.
Efficient beam splitting is observed for electron kinetic energies up to
$3\,$eV, in excellent agreement with particle tracking simulations. We discuss
prospects of this novel beam splitter approach for electron-based quantum
matter-wave optics experiments.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>Jakob Hammer</name>
    </author>
    <author>
      <name>Sebastian Thomas</name>
    </author>
