  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/1510.03988v2</id>
    <updated>2015-10-26T06:50:00Z</updated>
    <published>2015-10-14T08:02:34Z</published>
    <title>Interaction and multiband effects in intrinsic anomalous-Hall and
  spin-Hall effects of an interacting multiorbital metal</title>
    <summary>  Anomalous-Hall or spin-Hall effect generates, respectively, the charge or the
spin current perpendicular to an external electric field. However, a remaining
key challenge is to clarify effects of the electron-electron interaction. Here
I formulate the anomalous-Hall or spin-Hall effect intrinsic to the band
structure of an interacting multiorbital metal using the linear-response theory
with appropriate approximations, and show that the electron-electron
interaction induces a crossover without impurities from the damping-dependent
to the damping-independent anomalous-Hall or spin-Hall effect and a
characteristic correction of a non-conserved transport to the dc spin-Hall
conductivity at slightly low or high temperatures. Those are remarkable
interaction effects. I also show that in the presence of the electron-electron
interaction, the dominance of the interband excitations sometimes creates a
need to consider the excitations in the Fermi sea. This multiband effect
differs from the property of the resistivity, and the origin of that difference
is helpful to formulate other transports.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>Naoya Arakawa</name>
    </author>
    <arxiv:comment xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">29 pages (in single column format), 1 figure with Supplemental
