    <title>Central role of exchange-correlation hole in the 2D metal-insulator</title>
    <summary>  We show that the metal to insulator transition, whether generated by
decreasing the electron density or by increasing the spin alignment, is
determined by a universal functional form of the two-electron correlation
function g(r). This result provides direct evidence of the central role of the
Coulomb repulsion and exchange in driving the metal-insulator transition.
</summary>
