  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/1307.1490v1</id>
    <updated>2013-07-04T21:12:09Z</updated>
    <published>2013-07-04T21:12:09Z</published>
    <title>Zitterbewegung and the Magnetic Moment of the Electron</title>
    <summary>  Zitterbewegung of a Dirac electron is an oscillation between positive and
negative energy states, and is thus distinct from the analogous phenomena
exhibited by spin half charged particles in electric and magnetic fields.
Quantum field theory offers an insight into the velocity operator and provides
an interpretation of zitterbewegung. Applying stationary perturbation theory to
these results the electron $g$ factor is obtained analytically up to the
Schwinger correction ($g = 2 + \alpha/\pi $).
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>Basil S. Davis</name>
    </author>
    <arxiv:comment xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">4 figures</arxiv:comment>
    <link href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1307.1490v1" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <link title="pdf" href="http://arxiv.org/pdf/1307.1490v1" rel="related" type="application/pdf"/>
    <arxiv:primary_category xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom" term="quant-ph" scheme="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom"/>
    <category term="quant-ph" scheme="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom"/>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/1307.4020v1</id>
    <updated>2013-07-15T17:08:29Z</updated>
    <published>2013-07-15T17:08:29Z</published>
    <title>Ramsey-Bordé interferometer for electrons</title>
    <summary>  A scheme to realize an electron interferometer using low-intensity,
bi-chromatic laser pulses as beam splitter is proposed. The splitting process
is based on a modification of the Kapitza-Dirac effect, which produces a
momentum kick for electrons with a specific initial momentum. A full
interferometric setup in Ramsey-Bord\'e configuration is theoretically
analyzed.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>Karl-Peter Marzlin</name>
    </author>
    <arxiv:doi xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">10.1103/PhysRevA.88.043621</arxiv:doi>
