  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0006041v2</id>
    <updated>2000-08-16T17:09:28Z</updated>
    <published>2000-06-02T20:20:55Z</published>
    <title>Measuring Supernova Neutrino Temperatures using Lead Perchlorate</title>
    <summary>  Neutrino interactions with lead produce neutrons in numbers that depend on
neutrino energy and type. A detector based on lead perchlorate, for example,
would be able to measure the energy deposited by electrons and gammas in
coincidence with the number of neutrons produced. Sorting the electron energy
spectra by the number of coincident neutrons permits the identification of the
neutrino type that induced the reaction. This separation allows an analysis
which can determine the temperatures of electron neutrinos and electron
anti-neutrinos from a supernova in one experiment. The neutrino reaction
signatures of lead perchlorate and the fundamentals of using this material as a
neutrino detector are described.
</summary>
    <author>
      <name>S. R. Elliott</name>
    </author>
    <arxiv:doi xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">10.1103/PhysRevC.62.065802</arxiv:doi>
    <link title="doi" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevC.62.065802" rel="related"/>
    <arxiv:comment xmlns:arxiv="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom">minor changes, reference update</arxiv:comment>
